Now I can clearly see the regression. In PR #288449, the `ArchiveAgentSessionAction` was changed from:

```typescript
// BEFORE: Single session with proper showClearEditingSessionConfirmation 
async runWithSession(session: IAgentSession, accessor: ServicesAccessor): Promise<void> {
    const chatModel = chatService.getSession(session.resource);
    if (chatModel && !await showClearEditingSessionConfirmation(chatModel, dialogService, {
        isArchiveAction: true,
        titleOverride: ...,
        messageOverride: ...
    })) {
        return;
    }
    session.setArchived(true);
}
```

To:

```typescript
// AFTER: Multi-session support but lost the Keep/Undo dialog
async runWithSessions(sessions: IAgentSession[], accessor: ServicesAccessor): Promise<void> {
    // Just counts and shows a simple confirm dialog, no Keep/Undo options
    if (sessionsWithPendingChangesCount > 0) {
        const confirmed = await dialogService.confirm({...});
        if (!confirmed.confirmed) { return; }
    }
    for (const session of sessions) {
        session.setArchived(true);
    }
}
```

The old code used `showClearEditingSessionConfirmation` which offered "Keep & Continue" and "Undo & Continue" buttons that actually called `model.editingSession!.accept()` or `model.editingSession!.reject()`. The new code only shows a simple confirmation without offering to keep or undo edits, AND doesn't act on the editing session at all. So changes persist in the workspace after archiving.

